[
    {
        "content": "<p>I'll need something along the lines of the following.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">lemma</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Summable</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">prod_of_nonneg_of_summable_tsum</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">β</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">γ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">β</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">×</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">γ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h₁</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∀</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≤</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h₂</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∀</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Summable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">c</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↦</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">c</span><span class=\"o\">))</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h₃</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Summable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↦</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∑'</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">c</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">c</span><span class=\"o\">))</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"n\">Summable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I found <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=HasSum.of_sigma#doc\">docs#HasSum.of_sigma</a>, but this a) uses a Sigma type instead of a product type, and b) has a condition <code>(h : CauchySeq fun (s : Finset ((b : β) × γ b)) =&gt; ∑ i ∈ s, f i)</code>, which is a bit unwieldy (and I had problems translating this to the corresponding statement for the product type: it seems that there is no lemma allowing to transfer <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=CauchySeq#doc\">docs#CauchySeq</a> via an equivalence).</p>\n<p>There surely must be a better approach?</p>",
        "id": 483979900,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Stoll",
        "timestamp": 1732304821
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Would <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=HasProd.prod_fiberwise#doc\">docs#HasProd.prod_fiberwise</a> help?</p>",
        "id": 483988369,
        "sender_full_name": "Sébastien Gouëzel",
        "timestamp": 1732308189
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't think so; it requires <code>f</code> to be summable (for <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=HasSum.prod_fiberwise#doc\">docs#HasSum.prod_fiberwise</a>), which is what I want to prove.</p>",
        "id": 483988591,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Stoll",
        "timestamp": 1732308279
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No, sorry, I misread.</p>",
        "id": 483988646,
        "sender_full_name": "Sébastien Gouëzel",
        "timestamp": 1732308304
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, you could lift everything to ENNReal using the positivity, use my lemma there to see that the sum of <code>f</code> coincides with the sum in <code>h_3</code>, so that it is finite, and then come back to the reals. Not completely direct, but not unnatural because nonnegativity is crucial for your lemma.</p>",
        "id": 483988923,
        "sender_full_name": "Sébastien Gouëzel",
        "timestamp": 1732308448
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Which one is \"your lemma there\"?</p>",
        "id": 483988978,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Stoll",
        "timestamp": 1732308478
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"110050\">@Sébastien Gouëzel</span> <span aria-label=\"up\" class=\"emoji emoji-2b06\" role=\"img\" title=\"up\">:up:</span></p>",
        "id": 483990767,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Stoll",
        "timestamp": 1732309287
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"479359\">Michael Stoll</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/Summable.20for.20functions.20on.20product/near/483979900\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>it seems that there is no lemma allowing to transfer <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=CauchySeq#doc\">docs#CauchySeq</a> via an equivalence).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This sounds like it would be a good result to PR, irrespective of whether it's the right thing to do here</p>",
        "id": 483995043,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1732311466
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Though maybe it's <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=CauchySeq.comp_injective#doc\">docs#CauchySeq.comp_injective</a> ?</p>",
        "id": 483995470,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1732311646
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That is restricted to functions on <code>Nat</code>  and has an annoying <code>Nonempty</code> assumption.</p>",
        "id": 483995854,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Stoll",
        "timestamp": 1732311766
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What I would need is something that works for functions defined on <code>Finset &lt;something&gt;</code>.</p>",
        "id": 483995923,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Stoll",
        "timestamp": 1732311794
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>does <code>summable_prod_of_nonneg</code> help?</p>",
